node.text:
For the Academy Award-winning costume designer Ruth E. Carter, a project starts with research. “I read that script, I go on that journey. I immerse myself in the story,” she said.

Ruth, who’s known for her work on films including “Do the Right Thing,” “Malcolm X” and "Dolemite Is My Name," won an Oscar for her visionary work on “Black Panther.” But for her, success is about more than awards: “Winning is seeing your vision come to fruition,” she said. “That's winning.” 

We spent a day with Ruth, a member of our #BlackDesignVisionaries grant committee. Watch to hear about Spike Lee’s mentorship, her interview for “Black Panther” and more. #ShareBlackStories

The @nba. @carnegiehall. @nytmag. These are just a few of the household names Bobby C. Martin Jr. has worked with to create enduring branding and visual identity systems. “Redesigning an American institution is absolutely terrifying,” said Bobby, co-founder of the New York branding and design agency @championsdesign. “But it’s also thrilling.”

We spent a day with Bobby, a member of our #BlackDesignVisionaries grant committee, at his East Village studio. Watch to hear about his visionary approach to graphic design. #ShareBlackStories

"Listening is one of the most important skills for a designer," Ian said. "Learn to listen, to really hear what someone is saying and expressing. That’s how you understand problems more deeply, and it’s how you get to insights that help you come up with more elegant solutions."

#SomosLimitless 🎶 🎤 🎧 Use these new Instagram Story stickers by @marieryyoung to celebrate the Latinx community! For Mariery, who lives in Panama, #LatinxHeritageMonth is a celebration of family, culture, and honoring the past. “Being apart reminds us of the things we loved in our childhood, like carnavales and street parties,” she said. “I think that nostalgia connects our community.” Mariery, a Chinese-Latina illustrator, was also inspired by Latinx creators and future-makers. “This generation is celebrating and honoring these things that we were told weren’t to be celebrated, and they’re creating a beautiful new moment.”

Swipe to see all 3 stickers. To use them, open your Instagram Story tray and add your favorite to your story.

#LatinxHeritageMonth #DigitalIllustration #LHM #DigitalArt #StickerDesign

For the Academy Award-winning costume designer Ruth E. Carter, a project starts with research. “I read that script, I go on that journey. I immerse myself in the story,” she said.

Ruth, who’s known for her work on films including “Do the Right Thing,” “Malcolm X” and "Dolemite Is My Name," won an Oscar for her visionary work on “Black Panther.” But for her, success is about more than awards: “Winning is seeing your vision come to fruition,” she said. “That's winning.” 

We spent a day with Ruth, a member of our #BlackDesignVisionaries grant committee. Watch to hear about Spike Lee’s mentorship, her interview for “Black Panther” and more. #ShareBlackStories

#OutsideIn 🪴 Can you imagine starting your workday here? 💭 When designing @casafilipe, their home in Berlin, Moana Filipe and Leon Friess filled their minimal office with greenery. “To get into creative work, it helps to be surrounded by plants,” Moana said. “Plants have calming properties that we notice every day.” 

Although office environments are often uninspired, Moana and Leon used vegetation — including a Kentia palm and a cherry blossom branch from their grandmother’s garden — to create a warm space around their #EgonEirmann desk. With plants, Moana said, “you can change an uncomfortable space into an inviting home in seconds.” 🌸

#DesigninMotion 🌼 “I always loved problem solving as a kid,” said @drak_e.s (Drake Smith), a motion designer in California. Now, his work is all about solving problems: Each piece poses new challenges and requires multiple steps and iterations. For Drake, the biggest challenge is time. “If I spend hours on one small detail, the process would take forever.” ⏰

Drake started this piece by researching how flowers bloom, seeking to create a clay-inspired animation that moves organically. He focused on lighting, camera angles and material development, then applied the finishing touches: polishing and color correcting. This delicate flower took nearly 3 days to bloom — but for Drake the end result was worth it. 

Sound design by @sumeo.sd 🔊

#SundayShelfie 📚 “As a child, I dreamt of living in a library,” said @fabriksen (Elisabeth Riksen). After realizing that this probably wouldn’t happen, she scaled back: “I dreamt of having my own library with a ladder.” Here, the converted factory space that is now her Oslo apartment, that scaled-back dream came true. Elisabeth, who designed the library herself, hired a local contractor with a focus on reclaimed wood to build the shelves, rail and ladder. 🪜

The wall-to-wall unit goes beyond a display for Elisabeth’s significant book collection. “It’s practical, in that it houses my books and helps with the acoustics in the room,” she said. “It’s also ornamental, because it allows me to display art, plants and trinkets.” Another way she describes it: “Scandi minimalism done wrong.” 🪴

node.text: #OutsideIn 🪴 For his Parisian apartment, @home_jim_home (Jimmy Delpierre) created designated areas for different types of plants. The baby plants have settled into a nurturing station on the wall in the kitchen; plants that love light live on a shelf next to the window; and an ever-growing Monstera deliciosa has found a home in a large glass vase, so that Jimmy can watch the roots grow. For Jimmy, all of this specialized care is worth it: "This is the first thing I see when I get up in the morning, and it makes me smile." 🌿

#DesigninMotion ✨ “People get satisfied watching squishy things,” said @NikePurwitasarii, a designer from Jakarta, Indonesia. They want to watch “again and again” she added.

This animation is named after Blobby, a Jell-O-like creature from the animated series 𝐻𝑜𝑡𝑒𝑙 𝑇𝑟𝑎𝑛𝑠𝑦𝑙𝑣𝑎𝑛𝑖𝑎. But Disney movies initially inspired Nike to work in 3D animation. Through countless YouTube tutorials; lessons from her boyfriend, @divacndr, a motion designer; and trial and error, Nike has developed a style centered on cute, satisfying and colorful objects.  With each animation, Nike "tries so many times, until it looks just like the idea in my head." 💭

Note: This work was inspired by a piece by @vincentschwenk and @vitalygrossmann, which was posted on @vincentschwenk’s account in 2020.

#TheWorldNeedsMoreSpiralStaircases 🌀 When the avid architectural photographer @gabrielezocchi visited a friend in Zürich, Switzerland, he asked to see this marvel in the Altstetten neighborhood. Gabriele was in awe of the natural light leaking into the space, thanks to the steel wires circulating the inner core of the stairwell, creating a transparent effect. But the real “touch of magic” came when he stood directly beneath the stairs and looked up to see the spherical pendant lights, which reminded him of lava lamps — and gave the illusion of a much larger space. 🌋
